# Programming Fundamentals

## Function-First Development

**Principle**: Prioritize function-based implementation and develop with test-driven approach.

**Problem Pattern**: Unnecessary class creation increases complexity and makes testing difficult.

```typescript
// Anti-pattern: Creating class for simple processing
class DataProcessor {
	process(data: string): string {
		return data.toUpperCase();
	}
}
```

**Solution Pattern**: Prioritize pure function implementation and create testable designs.

### Early Return Pattern

**Principle**: Write with early returns as much as possible to keep nesting shallow.

**Problem Pattern**: Deep nesting reduces readability and increases complexity.

```typescript
// Anti-pattern: Deep nesting
function processUser(user: User | null): string | null {
	if (user) {
		if (user.isActive) {
			if (user.permissions.includes('read')) {
				if (user.profile) {
					return user.profile.displayName;
				} else {
					return null;
				}
			} else {
				return null;
			}
		} else {
			return null;
		}
	} else {
		return null;
	}
}
```

**Solution Pattern**: Create flat structure with early returns.

```typescript
// Pattern: Early return
function processUser(user: User | null): string | null {
	if (!user) return null;
	if (!user.isActive) return null;
	if (!user.permissions.includes('read')) return null;
	if (!user.profile) return null;

	return user.profile.displayName;
}
```

```typescript
// Pattern: Function-based implementation
function processData(data: string): string {
	return data.toUpperCase();
}

// Module-level caching example
const cache = new Map<string, ProcessedResult>();

function processWithCache(data: string): ProcessedResult {
	if (cache.has(data)) {
		return cache.get(data)!;
	}

	const result = expensiveProcess(data);
	cache.set(data, result);
	return result;
}

// Easy to test
test('processData should convert to uppercase', () => {
	expect(processData('hello')).toBe('HELLO');
});
```

## Strategic Class Usage

**Principle**: Use classes only for truly important concepts, clearly distinguishing between singletons and mass-produced instances.

**Class Usage Guidelines**:

- **Important concepts only**: Core concepts like engines, editors, managers
- **State management required**: When there's state shared across multiple methods
- **Lifecycle management**: When initialization and cleanup processes are needed

### Singleton Pattern

**Application Target**: Things that should have only one existence system-wide

```typescript
// Pattern: System-wide engine
class BurgerEditorEngine {
	private static instance?: BurgerEditorEngine;

	static getInstance(): BurgerEditorEngine {
		if (!this.instance) {
			this.instance = new BurgerEditorEngine();
		}
		return this.instance;
	}
}
```

### Instance Pattern

**Application Target**: Things that may be created multiple times

```typescript
// Pattern: Mass-produced items like blocks and items
class BurgerBlock {
	constructor(
		public readonly id: string,
		public readonly type: string,
	) {}
}
```

## Test-Driven Development

**Principle**: Base development on test-driven development, ideally practicing TDD.

**Testing Strategy**:

1. **Unit Tests**: vitest + JSDOM for component logic
2. **Integration Tests**: Playwright for user interactions
3. **Test First**: Write tests before implementation (TDD)

### Unit Testing Pattern

```typescript
// Pattern: Test-first development
describe('formatContent', () => {
	test('should format HTML content', () => {
		// Arrange
		const input = '<p>test</p>';
		const expected = '<p>test</p>';

		// Act
		const result = formatContent(input);

		// Assert
		expect(result).toBe(expected);
	});
});

// Implementation after tests
function formatContent(content: string): string {
	// Implement according to tests
	return content;
}
```

### Integration Testing Pattern

```typescript
// Pattern: User interaction testing with Playwright
test('should create new block', async ({ page }) => {
	await page.goto('/editor');
	await page.click('[data-testid="add-block"]');
	await page.click('[data-testid="text-block"]');

	const block = page.locator('[data-bge-name="text"]');
	await expect(block).toBeVisible();
});
```

## Testing Environment Guidelines

**Available Tools**:

- **vitest**: Unit testing framework
- **JSDOM**: DOM environment for component testing
- **Playwright**: End-to-end browser testing

**Testing Scope**:

- **Functions**: Always unit test
- **Classes**: Test public methods and state transitions
- **Integration**: Test user workflows with Playwright

### Test Organization

```typescript
// Pattern: Test file structure
// src/utils/format.ts
export function formatText(text: string): string {
	/* */
}

// src/utils/format.test.ts
import { formatText } from './format.js';

describe('formatText', () => {
	test('should handle empty string', () => {
		expect(formatText('')).toBe('');
	});
});
```

## State Management Strategy

**Principle**: Choose state management methods appropriately based on the nature and usage patterns of the state.

### Instance State

**Application Target**: State tightly coupled with complex logic

```typescript
// Pattern: Engine internal state
class BurgerEditorEngine {
	#isEditing: boolean = false;
	#selectedBlock: BurgerBlock | null = null;

	setEditMode(editing: boolean) {
		this.#isEditing = editing;
		// Complex state coordination logic
		this.#updateUI();
		this.#handlePermissions();
	}
}
```

### DOM State

**Application Target**: Display state and UI state

```typescript
// Pattern: State management with DOM attributes
function setBlockEditMode(element: HTMLElement, editing: boolean) {
	if (editing) {
		element.dataset.editing = 'true';
		element.classList.add('editing');
	} else {
		delete element.dataset.editing;
		element.classList.remove('editing');
	}
}

// CSS styling based on state
// .block[data-editing="true"] { border: 2px solid blue; }
```

### Event State

**Application Target**: Temporary notifications and state change propagation

```typescript
// Pattern: State propagation with events
function notifyBlockChange(block: BurgerBlock) {
	document.dispatchEvent(
		new CustomEvent('bge:block-change', {
			detail: { block },
		}),
	);
}

// Receiver side doesn't hold state, processes as needed
document.addEventListener('bge:block-change', (event) => {
	updateToolbar(event.detail.block);
	saveToHistory(event.detail.block);
});
```

### State Management Decision Tree

**When to choose Instance State**:

- ✅ State that coordinates with complex business logic
- ✅ State referenced and updated by multiple methods
- ✅ State requiring lifecycle management
- ✅ State requiring object-specific context

**When to choose DOM State**:

- ✅ Display/visibility state
- ✅ State requiring CSS integration
- ✅ State that should be persisted in HTML
- ✅ State that can be retrieved via DOM queries

**When to choose Event State**:

- ✅ Temporary notifications
- ✅ Loose coupling between components
- ✅ State change propagation
- ✅ Logging and history recording

## Design Decision Framework

**When to Use Functions**:

- ✅ Pure computations
- ✅ Data transformations
- ✅ Utility operations
- ✅ Stateless operations
- ✅ Module-level caching (Map, WeakMap, Set, WeakSet)

**When to Use Classes**:

- ✅ Core domain concepts (Engine, Block, Item)
- ✅ State management with multiple methods
- ✅ Lifecycle management (init, cleanup)
- ✅ Plugin/Extension systems

**When to Use Singletons**:

- ✅ Application engine
- ✅ Global configuration
- ✅ Event system
- ❌ Data storage (use instances)

**When to Use Instances**:

- ✅ Content entities (blocks, items)
- ✅ User interface components
- ✅ Temporary workers
- ✅ Data models

## Null vs Undefined Usage

**Principle**: Use `null` for explicit "no value" and `undefined` only in limited scenarios.

**Problem Pattern**: Returning `undefined` in union with other types creates unintended implicit value absence.

```typescript
// Anti-pattern: Returning undefined as a value
function findUser(id: string): User | undefined {
	return users.find((u) => u.id === id); // undefined is implicit
}

function getConfig(key: string): string | undefined {
	return config[key]; // undefined is unintentional
}
```

**Solution Pattern**: Use `null` for explicit "no value".

```typescript
// Pattern: Explicit null
function findUser(id: string): User | null {
	const user = users.find((u) => u.id === id);
	return user ?? null; // Intentional null
}

function getConfig(key: string): string | null {
	return config[key] ?? null; // Explicit no value
}
```

### Undefined Usage Guidelines

**When undefined/void usage is acceptable**:

- Standalone undefined not in union with other types
- Functions without explicit type definition (return type inferred as undefined)
- `Promise<void>` (expressing only async operation completion)

```typescript
// ✅ Acceptable usage examples
function logMessage(message: string) {
	// No type definition, returns only undefined
	console.log(message);
}

function processData(data: string) {
	// No return value, side effects only
	someGlobalState.push(data);
}

async function saveData(data: Data): Promise<void> {
	// Promise<void> is acceptable
	await api.save(data);
}

// ❌ Usage to avoid
function parseNumber(input: string): number | undefined {
	// Should be number | null
}
```

## Error Handling Pattern

**Principle**: Avoid deep nesting with try/catch, use `Promise.catch` and early returns for proper error handling.

**Problem Pattern**: Deep nesting with try/catch complicates code.

```typescript
// Anti-pattern: Deep try/catch nesting
async function processData(data: Data): Promise<Result | null> {
	try {
		const validated = validateData(data);
		try {
			const processed = await processValidData(validated);
			try {
				const saved = await saveData(processed);
				return saved;
			} catch (saveError) {
				console.error('Save failed:', saveError);
				return null;
			}
		} catch (processError) {
			console.error('Process failed:', processError);
			return null;
		}
	} catch (validationError) {
		console.error('Validation failed:', validationError);
		return null;
	}
}
```

**Solution Pattern**: Use `Promise.catch` with early returns and `instanceof` for error determination.

```typescript
// Pattern: Promise.catch with early returns
async function processData(data: Data): Promise<Result | null> {
	const validated = await validateData(data).catch((error) => error);
	if (validated instanceof Error) {
		console.error('Validation failed:', validated);
		return null;
	}

	const processed = await processValidData(validated).catch((error) => error);
	if (processed instanceof Error) {
		console.error('Process failed:', processed);
		return null;
	}

	const saved = await saveData(processed).catch((error) => error);
	if (saved instanceof Error) {
		console.error('Save failed:', saved);
		return null;
	}

	return saved;
}

// Pattern: No catch method needed when throwing errors directly
async function processDataStrict(data: Data): Promise<Result> {
	const validated = validateData(data); // Errors thrown as-is
	const processed = await processValidData(validated);
	const saved = await saveData(processed);
	return saved;
}

// Pattern: Handling specific error types
async function handleSpecificErrors(data: Data): Promise<Result | null> {
	const result = await processData(data).catch((error) => error);

	if (result instanceof ValidationError) {
		// Ignore validation errors
		return null;
	}

	if (result instanceof NetworkError) {
		// Network errors as retryable errors
		throw new RetryableError('Network issue, please retry');
	}

	if (result instanceof Error) {
		// Other errors as unexpected errors
		throw result;
	}

	return result;
}
```

### Error Handling Layers

**Principle**: Don't suppress exceptions at low layers or pure functions, catch at higher layers. Create identifiable Error subclasses.

**Error Hierarchy Design**:

```typescript
// Pattern: Custom Error class definitions
class ValidationError extends Error {
	constructor(
		message: string,
		public field: string,
	) {
		super(message);
		this.name = 'ValidationError';
	}
}

class NetworkError extends Error {
	constructor(
		message: string,
		public statusCode?: number,
	) {
		super(message);
		this.name = 'NetworkError';
	}
}

class ProcessingError extends Error {
	constructor(
		message: string,
		public data?: unknown,
	) {
		super(message);
		this.name = 'ProcessingError';
	}
}
```

**Layer-based Error Handling**:

```typescript
// Low-level: Pure functions throw exceptions as-is
function validateEmail(email: string): string {
	if (!email.includes('@')) {
		throw new ValidationError('Invalid email format', 'email');
	}
	return email.trim().toLowerCase();
}

function parseUserData(json: string): UserData {
	try {
		return JSON.parse(json);
	} catch {
		throw new ProcessingError('Invalid JSON format');
	}
}

// Mid-level: Business logic also basically throws
async function fetchUserProfile(id: string): Promise<UserProfile> {
	const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);

	if (!response.ok) {
		throw new NetworkError(`Failed to fetch user: ${response.status}`, response.status);
	}

	const json = await response.text();
	return parseUserData(json); // Errors propagate as-is
}

// High-level: Catch at public API or class level
class UserService {
	async getUser(id: string): Promise<UserProfile | null> {
		try {
			const profile = await fetchUserProfile(id);
			const validatedEmail = validateEmail(profile.email);
			return { ...profile, email: validatedEmail };
		} catch (error) {
			if (error instanceof ValidationError) {
				console.warn(`Validation failed for user ${id}:`, error.field);
				return null;
			}

			if (error instanceof NetworkError && error.statusCode === 404) {
				return null; // User not found
			}

			// Other errors re-thrown (unexpected errors)
			throw error;
		}
	}
}
```

**Error Boundaries**:

```typescript
// Pattern: Error handling at appropriate layers
// 1. Utility Layer: Throw exceptions
function formatDate(date: Date): string {
	if (!(date instanceof Date) || isNaN(date.getTime())) {
		throw new ValidationError('Invalid date object', 'date');
	}
	return date.toISOString();
}

// 2. Service Layer: Business logic error transformation
async function createUser(userData: CreateUserRequest): Promise<User> {
	const validatedEmail = validateEmail(userData.email); // Throw as-is
	const formattedDate = formatDate(userData.birthDate); // Throw as-is

	// Service-specific error handling
	const response = await fetch('/api/users', {
		method: 'POST',
		body: JSON.stringify({
			...userData,
			email: validatedEmail,
			birthDate: formattedDate,
		}),
	});

	if (!response.ok) {
		throw new NetworkError(`User creation failed: ${response.status}`, response.status);
	}

	return response.json();
}

// 3. API Layer: User-facing error responses
export async function handleCreateUser(req: Request): Promise<Response> {
	try {
		const user = await createUser(req.body);
		return Response.json({ success: true, user });
	} catch (error) {
		if (error instanceof ValidationError) {
			return Response.json(
				{
					success: false,
					error: 'Validation failed',
					field: error.field,
				},
				{ status: 400 },
			);
		}

		if (error instanceof NetworkError) {
			return Response.json(
				{
					success: false,
					error: 'Service unavailable',
				},
				{ status: 503 },
			);
		}

		// Log unexpected errors then return 500
		console.error('Unexpected error:', error);
		return Response.json(
			{
				success: false,
				error: 'Internal server error',
			},
			{ status: 500 },
		);
	}
}
```
